Serialization and Deserialization in Java -

Whenever we create an object in Java, it exists only while the program is running (inside RAM).

// Student s = new Student("Ekta", 101);

But with the help of serialization, we can -
save it in a file
send it over internet
store it in database
use it later after program closes

Java cannot directly store objects in files.
So Java converts the object into bytes.
This process is called Serialization

And when we convert those bytes back into object then it is called Deserialization.

Real-life example -
Suppose you have a toy car.
Keeping it in a box for transport = Serialization
Opening the box and getting back the toy = Deserialization
Object → bytes → object

Serialization-Converting an object into byte stream. (Object → Byte Stream)
Deserialization-Converting byte stream back into object. (Byte Stream → Object)

It is used for -
saving object in file
sending object over network
caching
storing session data
-------------------------------------------------------------------
To serialize an object, class must implement:
Serializable interface

It is a marker interface.
Marker interface means:
interface with no methods

Example -
Step 1: Create Serializable Class
import java.io.Serializable;

class Student implements Serializable {

    int id;
    String name;

    Student(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }
}

It is important to implement Serializable interface because it tells JVM:
"This object is allowed to be converted into bytes." Without this, serialization will fail

Step 2: Serialization Example
import java.io.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Student s1 = new Student(101, "Ekta");
        // Connect file
        FileOutputStream fos =
                new FileOutputStream("student.txt");

        // Convert object into bytes
        ObjectOutputStream oos =
                new ObjectOutputStream(fos);

        // Write object
        oos.writeObject(s1);

        oos.close();
        fos.close();

        System.out.println("Object Serialized");
    }
}

What gets stored in Demo file?
Not readable text because object is stored in binary form.

Deserialization Example-

Now we will read object back from file.

import java.io.*;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("student.txt");

        ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);

        // Read object
        Student s = (Student) ois.readObject();

        ois.close();
        fis.close();

        System.out.println(s.id);
        System.out.println(s.name);
    }
}

Output
101
Ekta

Object restored successfully.


Student Object
       ↓
Serialization
       ↓
Byte Stream/File
       ↓
Deserialization
       ↓
Student Object Again

Serializable is Mandatory

Without: implements Serializable, you get: NotSerializableException
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
transient Keyword

Sometimes we don't want some fields to be serialized, then use transient keyword.

Example:
password
OTP
temporary data

Example:

class Student implements Serializable {

    String name;

    transient String password;
}

Now password will NOT be saved.

Example
Student s = new Student();

s.name = "Ekta";
s.password = "abc123";

After deserialization:

name = Ekta
password = null

password is null because transient fields are skipped.
-----------------------------------------------------------------
static Variables are NOT Serialized-

Static belongs to class, not object.

Example:

static String college = "ABC";

This is not stored during serialization.
